# DFL Game Project Patterns

This project is built on `com.deepforestlabs.framework`. All game logic flows through DI containers, IRunnable states, and MVC controllers.

## States as IRunnables

Each game phase is an `IRunnable` that runs inside its own container scope. Register with `AddTransient<IRunnable, T>()` and run with `container.Run<IRunnable>(token)`.

```csharp
public sealed class SessionState : IRunnable
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IContainer _container = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly LevelContainerFactory _levelFactory = default!;

    public async UniTask Run(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // show title, wait for input, then load level
            await using (IContainer level = await _container
                .CreateChild("Level")
                .AddFromBuilder(_levelFactory)
                .AddScene(levelDef.SceneRef)
                .Build(token))
            {
                await level.Run<IRunnable>(token);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Container Hierarchy

Game projects build a chain of nested container scopes. Each scope has a `ContainerBuilderFactory` ScriptableObject:

```
Main (framework)
  -> App (SlumberContainerFactory)
    -> Session (SessionContainerFactory)
      -> Level (LevelContainerFactory)
        -> Gameplay (GameplayContainerFactory)
```

Each factory registers its scope's services, child factories, and runnable:

```csharp
public sealed class SessionContainerFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private LevelContainerFactory _levelFactory = default!;
    [SerializeField] private LevelDefinition _defaultLevel = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        return builder
            .AddScoped<ICursorService, CursorService>()
            .AddSingleton(_levelFactory)
            .AddSingleton(_defaultLevel)
            .AddTransient<IRunnable, SessionState>();
    }
}
```

## MVC Pattern

UI features use the framework's MVC system. Each feature has four parts:

**Model** -- serializable data record with an enum ID. No logic.

```csharp
[Serializable]
public record HudModel : Model<HudModelId>
{
    [SerializeField] private float _crosshairRestSize = 24f;
    public float CrosshairRestSize => _crosshairRestSize;
}
```

**View** -- MonoBehaviour implementing `IView`. Pure display, setter methods only. No business logic.

```csharp
public class HudView : MonoBehaviour, IView
{
    [SerializeField] private TMP_Text loadedAmmoText = default!;

    public void SetAmmo(int loaded, int reserve) { /* update UI */ }

    public UniTask OpenAnimation(CancellationToken token) => UniTask.CompletedTask;
    public void OpenAnimationFinished() { }
    public UniTask CloseAnimation(CancellationToken token) => UniTask.CompletedTask;
    public void CloseAnimationFinished() { }
}
```

**Controller** -- orchestrates model and view. Receives dependencies via `[Dependency]`.

```csharp
public sealed class HudController : Controller<HudModel, HudView>
{
    [Dependency] private readonly PlayerController _player = default!;

    protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(HudView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            await UniTask.Yield(PlayerLoopTiming.LastUpdate, token);
            view.SetCrosshairSize(/* ... */);
        }
        return default;
    }
}
```

**Factory** -- ScriptableObject that wires the MVC triad into a container. Registered as a child in the parent factory.

```csharp
[FactoryMenuItem("HUD", "Slumber")]
public sealed class HudFactory : Factory<HudModelId, HudModel, HudView, HudController> { }
```

Wire MVC factories into gameplay via `AddChild`:

```csharp
public sealed class GameplayContainerFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private PlayerFactory _playerFactory = default!;
    [SerializeField] private HudFactory _hudFactory = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        return builder
            .AddChild(_playerFactory)
            .AddChild(_hudFactory)
            .AddTransient<IRunnable, GameplayState>();
    }
}
```

## Reactive State with AsyncReactiveProperty

The framework uses UniTask's `AsyncReactiveProperty<T>` (from `Cysharp.Threading.Tasks`) for observable, change-notifying state. Prefer reactive properties over C# events for any state that multiple consumers need to read or observe.

### How the MVC model is wired

The `Factory` base class automatically wraps the model in `AsyncReactiveProperty<TModel>` during container build. Controllers receive it via `[Dependency]` and access it through the `Model` property:

```csharp
// Framework does this internally -- you do NOT write this yourself:
builder.AddScoped(_ => new AsyncReactiveProperty<TModel>(_model));

// In your controller, the base class exposes:
//   Model (get/set)        -- read or replace the current model
//   ModelUpdated            -- IUniTaskAsyncEnumerable<TModel> for async iteration
//   _model.WaitAsync(token) -- UniTask<TModel> that completes on next change
```

Setting `Model = newModel` triggers reactive notifications. Call `Refresh()` to re-notify without changing the model reference.

### Shared reactive state via DI

For state that multiple services or controllers need to observe, register an `AsyncReactiveProperty<T>` in a `ContainerBuilderFactory`. Do NOT use C# events (`event Action<T>`) for cross-component state.

```csharp
// GOOD -- register reactive state in a factory
public sealed class GameContainerFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private SessionConfig _defaultConfig = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        return builder
            .AddScoped(_ => new AsyncReactiveProperty<SessionConfig>(_defaultConfig))
            .AddScoped<ISessionService, SessionService>()
            .AddTransient<IRunnable, GameState>();
    }
}

// GOOD -- service writes .Value, any consumer reads or observes
public sealed class SessionService : ISessionService
{
    [Dependency] private readonly AsyncReactiveProperty<SessionConfig> _config = default!;

    public void UpdateConfig(SessionConfig config) => _config.Value = config;
}

// GOOD -- controller awaits changes
public sealed class LobbyController : Controller<LobbyModel, LobbyView>
{
    [Dependency] private readonly AsyncReactiveProperty<SessionConfig> _config = default!;

    protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(LobbyView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var config in _config.WithoutCurrent().WithCancellation(token))
        {
            view.SetRegion(config.Region);
        }
        return default;
    }
}

// BAD -- C# events require manual subscribe/unsubscribe, miss initial state,
//         and hold references after disposal
public event Action<SessionConfig>? ConfigChanged;
```

### Read-only interface pattern

When a service owns mutable state but consumers should only observe, expose `IReadOnlyAsyncReactiveProperty<T>` on the interface:

```csharp
public interface IPauseService
{
    IReadOnlyAsyncReactiveProperty<bool> IsPaused { get; }
    void Pause();
    void Resume();
}

public sealed class PauseService : IPauseService, IDisposable
{
    private readonly AsyncReactiveProperty<bool> _isPaused = new(false);

    public IReadOnlyAsyncReactiveProperty<bool> IsPaused => _isPaused;

    public void Pause() => _isPaused.Value = true;
    public void Resume() => _isPaused.Value = false;
    public void Dispose() => _isPaused.Dispose();
}
```

### Key API

| Method | Returns | Purpose |
|--------|---------|---------|
| `.Value` (get/set) | `T` | Read or write current value; setting notifies all subscribers |
| `.WaitAsync(token)` | `UniTask<T>` | Completes on the next value change |
| `.WithoutCurrent()` | `IUniTaskAsyncEnumerable<T>` | Async stream that skips the current value |
| `GetAsyncEnumerator()` | `IUniTaskAsyncEnumerator<T>` | `await foreach` -- yields current value first, then changes |
| `.Dispose()` | `void` | Completes all subscribers |

### When to use C# events vs reactive properties

| Scenario | Use |
|----------|-----|
| Observable state that consumers read AND subscribe to | `AsyncReactiveProperty<T>` |
| State shared across multiple controllers/services via DI | `AsyncReactiveProperty<T>` registered in factory |
| Read-only observable state on a service interface | `IReadOnlyAsyncReactiveProperty<T>` |
| One-shot fire-and-forget notification with no state | C# `event` is acceptable |

## Prohibited: FindAnyObjectByType and Unity Global Accessors

Scene MonoBehaviours and Unity singletons must be resolved through DI, never through Unity's `Find*` methods or global accessors. These bypass the container, produce untracked null references, and prevent the DI system from failing fast on missing dependencies.

```csharp
// BAD -- bypasses DI, null result is silent, no lifecycle management
var view = Object.FindAnyObjectByType<TitleScreenView>();
if (view == null) { /* silent fallback */ }

// BAD -- global accessor, can be null (wrong tag, destroyed, race condition)
Camera cam = Camera.main;

// BAD -- same problem under a different name
var controller = FindObjectOfType<PixelPipelineController>();

// GOOD -- scene MonoBehaviour registered via AddScene<T>, resolved by container
// In the ContainerBuilderFactory:
builder.AddScene<TitleScreenView>(sceneRef);
// In the consuming class:
[Dependency] private readonly TitleScreenView _view = default!;

// GOOD -- MVC view resolved through Factory (preferred for UI features)
// Factory registers Model, View, Controller as a unit via AddChild
builder.AddChild(_titleScreenFactory);
// Controller receives the view via its Run method parameter

// GOOD -- camera registered in container, injected where needed
[Dependency] private readonly Camera _camera = default!;
```

If a MonoBehaviour exists in a loaded scene, use `AddScene<T>` to register it. If it's a UI feature, use the MVC Factory pattern. The container throws `GameException` or `DiException` if the object is missing -- no silent nulls.

## Services

Define an interface, implement as a class, register via `AddScoped<IService, Impl>()`:

```csharp
public interface IInputService
{
    Vector2 MoveInput { get; }
    bool FirePressed { get; }
}

public sealed class InputService : IInputService, IInitializable, IDisposable
{
    [Dependency] private readonly InputActionAsset _actions = default!;

    public UniTask Initialize(CancellationToken token) { /* bind actions */ }
    public void Dispose() { /* unbind */ }
}
```

